  "created_at": "2016-12-19T03:12:08Z",
  "updated_at": "2017-03-01T06:51:24Z",
  "closed_at": null,
  "body": "## background\r\n\r\nCurrently we can just describe length through a number which are the pixels of the length. In many situation, for example when we want to set a length to 50% of the screen's width or height, it need to make a calc.\r\n\r\n## Purpose\r\n\r\nThis proposal is for writing CSS length with more popular and standard values more easily.\r\n\r\n## Details\r\n\r\nDevelopers can use `100vw`, `2rem` in `<style>` and inline style. At the same time in JavaScript runtime. `weex.unit.vw(100)`, `weex.unit.rem(2)` are both OK.\r\n\r\nrefs: [Distance Units in W3C CSS Values and Units Module](https://www.w3.org/TR/css-values-3/#lengths)\r\n\r\n### Changes for Render Layer\r\n\r\n(nothing to change)\r\n\r\n### Changes for JS Runtime\r\n\r\n* Pass through these CSS values in Weex transformer: `vw`, `vh`, `rem`, `cm`, `mm`, `q`, `in`, `pt`, `pc`, `px`\r\n* Calculate each CSS units and set them into `weex.unit` instance object.\r\n\r\n### Changes for Tools\r\n\r\n(nothing to change)\r\n\r\n### Changes for Dev Experiences\r\n\r\n* Developers can use `100vw`, `3rem`... in `<style>` and inline style.\r\n* Developers can use `weex.unit.vw(100)` ... in `<script>` and JavaScript lib files.\r\n\r\n## Notes\r\n\r\n(none)",
  "closed_by": null
